+Jon B You live in Arizona, and are complaining about 'Liberals' ?  What a 
big surprise..

The problem is much simplier than all that. The problem is liberalism. 
Liberalism and political correctness permeate the news media. It is usually 
apparent in the liberal biases but in this case it was apparent in one 
person's insistence that another submit to their will. Liberals are at war 
with individualism, and I defend Joan Rivers' right to be who she is as I 
would do with anyone. Anything that opposes individualism is opposed to 
freedom and is ultimately un-American. I don't friend people on here, but 
if you're on Facebook send a friend request to Jon Berryman in Phoenix, 
Arizona.

I believe that offending people makes it a lot harder to convince them of 
my viewpoint.

I rarely have been in a situation where a direct insult has convinced me 
that I am wrong.  Instead, it makes me think that the other person is 
insensitive and mean, so they're probably wrong.

Is that a rational assumption?  No.  But, I'm a human, and I am very prone 
to being irrational.

So, because I assume other people are human like me, I try to choose my 
words carefully, so they don't act as irrationally as I would.

This leads to me using technical terms and long statements.  Some people 
would call that "political correctness."

I imagine Fredricka Whitfield had a similar mindset.  To be honest, it 
seemed like she had these problems with Joan River's comedy

1) Joan Rivers jokes sometimes come at the cost of other's people's feelings

2) Joan Rivers made jokes about tragic events like Princess Diana's death, 
and the death of Casey Anthony's baby.

Unfortunately for Fredricka, she spent WAAAAAAAAYYYYYYYYY too long trying 
to bring up these ideas in a politically correct way.  She tried to use 
technical terms and long statements.

Fredericka's biggest crime was that she monologued.  She asked enormously 
huge questions.  You can see several parts of the tape where Joan would 
like to answer, but Fredericka is still talking.

That's inconsiderate.

And I'm a total hypocrite for saying that, because I am prone to 
monologuing myself.  It's something I need to work on.

When she brought up the case of the furs, Fredericka probably didn't give a 
crap about furs.  I get the impression she was trying to point out that 
Joan isn't afraid to push boundaries, and that's why people enjoy her humor.

But Joan probably had gotten tired of trying to defend her viewpoint and 
not getting talked over.  It would be easier to feel that way after being 
talked over for so long, and Fredericka's poisoned-honey approach to asking 
thorny questions.

It makes sense why she would be offended, and why she would see a reason to 
walk out.

So, based on my limited perspective of only about 2 minutes of this 
interview, I would say both people are at fault here.

Joan should have enough experience to handle criticism.  She's a famous 
comedian, and she has years of experience.  If she had been able to make a 
joke about the predicament she was in, I would have given her props for 
being able to handle that situation effectively.

It especially seems hypocritical for her to be able to dismiss the idea 
that she can joke about tragedy and death, but can't handle being in the 
hot-seat for that.

How can she expect people to deal with the distress of death through humor, 
when she can't deal the distress of a poorly-executed TV interview through 
humor?

Fredericka needs to be more direct in what her opinions and views are, 
especially when her interviewing questions are thorny.  Her body language 
clearly shows how much she disagrees with Joan's humor.  Masking it with 
carefully poised, wordy questions really didn't help her out.

Both women could use this situation to consider how they can be more civil 
in their  own discourse, but it seems likely that they will use it to 
consider how the OTHER woman could have been more civil in THEIR discourse. 
 I hope they don't.

And I hope us Youtube commentators don't eihter.

I apologize for being a windbag.  Send me a friend request if you made it 
this far.

TLDR: Both of the women could have been more considerate, and hopefully 
they will examine how they personally could have made the conversation go 
better.

I disagree that Joan Rivers was being a baby. Indeed, she was being the 
grown up. Yes, the questions may have been worth asking, but this scripted 
media stooge-ette became pushy and almost preachy when she didn't get the 
answers she wanted. It's clear that the  'hypersensitives' in the news 
media, as part of their pipe dream utopian cause, are hellbent on 
preventing old-timers in stand up comedy from displaying old-fashioned 
brashness. Joan Rivers is 81 and not about to have this type of political 
correctness, that permeates the media, shoved down her throat. The 
'in-your-face approach is rude, but it becomes entertaining when the 
interviewee throws it right back in the face of the interviewer.

It was clear that Joan was being fairly sensitive and a bit of a baby. 
 It's too bad she didn't stick around longer, I'm pretty sure eventually 
she would have been asked "What the hell is wrong with your face?"

Jon, I would agree that the reporter was unnecessarily beating around the 
bush with someone who, I expect, has the maturity to handle direct 
criticism.

Often, attempts to be unoffensive can lead to unclear communication.  That 
was certainly the case here.  The reporter's thorny questions sugar-coated 
in diplomacy were certainly a mistake, and hindered the open discourse that 
the news should encourage.

I still think those questions were worth asking, but ironically asking them 
more bluntly would have been less offensive.

Allow me to shed some not so biased light on the situation: I have studied 
mass media and journalism and I have also studied comedy. Let me tell you 
all that Joan Rivers has saved my life. I know that for a lot of you that's 
a huge stretch but hear me out. A few years ago I was going through 
depression and I stumbled upon Joan on Comedy Central and I decided to 
research her other material. As much as I initially felt offended by some 
of her material, she taught me not to be so uptight and that a sign of 
maturity is to laugh at yourself and your hardships. I highly respect Joan 
and all that she's done. That being said I don't hate this interviewer and 
I don't think it was her intention to be derogatory to Joan or her career. 
I just don't think she got it. I think a lot more would have come out of 
this interview if it was another comedian or someone who was a fan of 
Joan's humour conducting the interview but that clearly didn't happen. To 
those of you hating on Joan, please "grow up." With people like me, she has 
saved lives with her comedy. And she surely doesn't need people telling her 
how to do her job, which is why I think she walked off. While I think Joan 
can be a bitch, that's why I love her: she's not afraid to push the 
envelope in a society that desperately needs it. Just leave people to their 
vices and what they're good at.

of the character April Grace played in a 2002 ep. of the CBS drama

investigative reporting brought down shady nightclub operator Freddy Cattan 
(Christian Camargo). At the end of the ep., Delia is seen talking with 
death row inmate Winston, played by Mane Andrew (credited as Mane Andrews), 
telling him information she uncovered would likely get him exonerated and 
change state law. It turned out a key piece of evidence, a jacket, wasn’t 
properly DNA tested for blood residue.

Note: April Grace as closeted lesbian TV reporter Delia Rivers, along with 
Dan Butler as David Wilkins and Josh Hopkins as Eric Keller could evoke 
1/13/12 condolence calls, but not Hawaii-born Obama’s White House 
spokesman, Josh Earnest. Still, Earnest was born in Kansas City, MO on the 
day Osama bin Laden turned 20 years old: 3/10/77.

While “Without a Trace” character Winston (Mane Andrew) is unrelated, Joan 
Rivers’ late husband, Edgar Rosenberg, died in Philadelphia on Aug. 14, 
1987, which is unrelated to Winston-Salem, NC-born actress Jackée Harry 
turning 31 years old that day. It was the same day 2007 HEisMAN Trophy 
winning Florida Gators quarterback Tim Tebow was born in the Philippines.

Still, Mane Andrew appeared in the 2004 Katie Holmes, U.S. 
presidency-themed film, “First Daughter”—as did Joan Rivers.

Andrew played the boyfriend of the college dorm room mate of the title 
character, Samantha MacKenzie (Holmes)—the daughter of President MacKenzie 
(Michael Keaton).

news for comically suggesting the current “real life” U.S. president, 
Barack Hussein Obama, is a closeted homosexual who is married to a 
t=R=A=n-zy. As proof, Joan called on those interested to check out the

From media report:

The octogenarian comic was approached by a cameraman in New York City and 
asked: “Do you think the United States will see the first gay president or 
the first woman president?”

Her response: “We already have it with Obama, so let’s just calm down.”

From Wikipedia:

Rivers was born Joan Alexandra Molinsky in Brooklyn, New York, in 1933, the 
daughter of Russian Jewish immigrants Beatrice (née Grushman; January 6, 
1906 – October 1975) and Meyer C. Molinsky (December 7, 1900 – January 
1985). Her older sister Barbara died on June 3, 2013, aged 82

Joan's older sister, Barbara, died on 6/3/13—the same day U.S. Sen. Frank 
Raleigh Lautenberg (D-NJ) died, making way for fellow Democrat Cory A. 
Booker to succeed him by winning a special election in October. It's 
unrelated to Cory Aquino's "People Power" revolution over the corrupt 
Marcos regime in the Philippines or "He who has the gold, makes the rule". 
But, Joan did lots of  Imelda Marcos jokes back in the day.

Personal note:

I have been surprised at the nasty comments directed toward Rivers since 
her health crisis began in August 2014. I don’t watch much she does these 
days, but really enjoyed her in my late teens and early 20s, circa 
1986-1994.

I felt a strange connection to the roll out of her comeback “The Joan 
Rivers Show” in 1989 since it’s debut coincided with my beginning life as a 
college student. In the year before the premiere, I had spent idle time 
behind the board reading trade publications that had full page ads for the 
still developing show, showing what percentage of the country it had 
“cleared”. It was at a time in my life when it felt like anything was 
possible, so I indulged.

Note: In those same trade publications, I also saw full page ads for “The 
Faye Wattleton Show”, (think Planned Parenthood), which I’m not sure ever 
aired. If it did, it didn’t last long. Unrelated to the “B-word”, Wattleton 
was born Alyce Faye Wattleton on July 8, 1943 in St. Louis, MO.

I was lucky enough to speak with Joan on her WOR-AM radio call-in show in 
the late 1990s. She could not have been nicer in the minute or so that I 
had with her. It was at a time that I was listening to lots of talk radio 
and still somewhat engaged with society. And, I was surprised to both get 
through and get on the show that night—a difficult enough task when dealing 
with abrupt show producers and call screeners. Doubly difficult if your 
life is being secretly monitored.

Note: “First Daughter” was directed by Forest Whitaker (“The Crying Game”; 
“Phone Booth”; “The Last King of Scotland”) and whether Barack is gay or 
Michelle LaVaughn is transgendered, Whitaker hosted the 2/10/07 edition of 
NBC’s venerable sketch comedy show, “Saturday Night Live”, on the same day 
Obama officially launched his presidential campaign from Springfield, IL.

Note: Without getting phallic, it’s worth mentioning that in February 2013, 
Whitaker was accused of stealing salami by an employee of the Milano 
Market, a deli in Manhattan’s Morningside Heights neighborhood. Apparently 
unaware of the Oscar winner’s identity, the employee stopped Whitaker in 
the store and frisked him, only to discover that he hadn’t stolen anything. 
Deli begins like Delia Rivers.

While Joan Rivers’ daughter, Melissa Warburg Rosenberg Rivers, won’t ever 
be “First Daughter” like Sasha and Malia Obama in “real life” and Katie 
Holmes in film, Melissa did turn 41 years old the day Obama became #44: 
January 20, 2009.﻿

Comedy is a fine line between having fun, usually at specific situation, 
personal experience, an institution, or at someone's expense;p or being 
insensitive to the feelings of others.

Joan Rivers, broke the glass ceiling for all female want-to-be comedians. 
She has paid her dues. She has endured the ruff tuff world of male 
domination of comedy.

Joan is not a Lucille Ball, but a stand-up comedian like Phyllis Diller, 
telling jokes as one liners. She has a lot in common with Don Rickles style 
of comedy. She can be harsh, critical, over bearing, excreta but she can be 
on spot with the zingers which are at times hilarious.

Joan Rivers does have a heart of gold. She will take time to help out those 
that need it. She is in her 80's. Her only goal in life is to make others 
laugh. Joan Rivers believes that when life is difficult and unbearable, 
find something to laugh at. It will help you bear under the weight that is 
burdening your soul. Whether it is a hit or miss, comedy is difficult path 
to achieve. So cut this Lady some slack, take her comments with a grain of 
salt, and don't take her to serious. Perhaps you will learn not to take 
yourself so serious too. If you can not laugh at yourself then you are not 
worth a damn.﻿
